Reason: The compound 5-Norbornene-2,3-dimethanol is based on the norbornene structure, which itself is a bicyclic structure derived from cyclopentene. Since a basic cyclopentene molecule has a melting point around -94°C, the bicyclic norbornene structure will be significantly higher due to the added ring strain and rigidity. We can estimate this increase to be around +100°C. Adding hydroxyl groups (–OH) to a molecule generally increases the melting point due to hydrogen bonding. Each hydroxyl group attached to the norbornene structure will contribute to this effect, we can estimate this increase to be around +40°C for each hydroxyl group. Therefore, we expect a total increase of around +80°C from the two hydroxyl groups. Considering both the bicyclic structure and the hydroxyl groups, the predicted melting point increase would be 100 + 80 = +180°C when compared to basic cyclopentene.
